1560 S. Halkiotis et al. / Signal Processing 87 (2007) 1559‚Äì1568

carcinomas reveal microcalciÔ¨Åcations upon histological examination [4]. MicrocalciÔ¨Åcations are tiny granular deposits of calcium that appear on the mammogram as small bright spots. A radiologist must carefully examine the mammogram with a magniÔ¨Åer to locate calciÔ¨Åcations, which may be embedded in dense tissue. In the past several years there has been a considerable interest in developing methods for automatic detection of microcalciÔ¨Åcations in mammograms [5]. Several methods have been proposed in the literature for their segmentation [6]. In this paper we present a new method for automatic segmentation and classiÔ¨Åcation of microcalciÔ¨Åcations using morphological reconstruction. MicrocalciÔ¨Åcations were extracted from their background and segmented through evaluation of their topographic representation. The novelty of our approach lies in the exploitation of mathematical morphology properties. Indeed, mathematical morphology provides tools for the extraction of microcalciÔ¨Åcations even if they are located on a non-uniform background. After extraction of the microcalciÔ¨Åcation from its background, a set of characteristic features was extracted for classiÔ¨Åcation purposes. The extracted features were classiÔ¨Åed using ArtiÔ¨Åcial Neural Network classiÔ¨Åers. We evaluated the performance of two different neural network architectures: the multi-layer perceptron and the radial basis function neural network, on the basis of a set of real Ô¨Åeld mammograms of a standard database. 2. The proposed feature extraction method Mathematical morphology can be described as a theory for the analysis of spatial structures [7]. It is called morphology because it aims at analyzing the shape and form of objects. The basic tools of mathematical morphology are the morphological operations. A morphological operation P transforms an image A by means of a structuring element B (which can be chosen by the user) into a new image P (A; B). The basic morphological operations are dilation and erosion [8]. Based on the notion of geodesic distance, we can deÔ¨Åne geodesic dilation and geodesic erosion. A geodesic dilation involves two images: a marker image and a mask image. Both images must have the same deÔ¨Ånition domain. Given a mask X, the geodesic dilation of size nX0 of Y within X is the set of pixels of X whose geodesic distance to Y is

