where the operand ‚Äò‚Äò_‚Äô‚Äô denotes point-wise maximum operation and ‚Äò‚ÄòdI(n)‚Äô‚Äô denotes the n-fold dilation on image J, using a certain structuring element. Stopping point n is reached when a single pixel of the dilated image J becomes equal (in gray level value) to a pixel in I. A grayscale image can be seen as a topographical relief or landscape, where each pixel is represented as an elevation proportional to its intensity or gray level value. Therefore, the dark and light structures of the image correspond to the valleys and the domes of this relief, respectively. A plateau located at the top of such domes, constitutes a regional maximum. MicrocalciÔ¨Åcations appear on digitized mammograms as bright spots. These spots are small regions with intensity values higher than their surroundings or background. Each microcalciÔ¨Åcation constitutes a regional maximum. Fig. 1 shows a cluster of microcalciÔ¨Åcations and Fig. 2 the topographic representation of this region, where microcalciÔ¨Åcations appear as domes with higher intensity values than the surrounding tissue. Image maxima constitute an important morphological feature, because they can mark image objects with speciÔ¨Åc characteristics. Mammograms are complex images with a large number of regional maxima. In order to detect microcalciÔ¨Åcations we have to evaluate the dynamics of each regional maximum. The notion of dynamics

