objects extracted from six randomly selected mammograms. The training set was composed of three mammograms with one cluster, one mammogram with two clusters and two normal mammograms. The rest of the mammograms containing microcalciÔ¨Åcations and thirty normal mammograms were used in the testing phase. None of the mammograms was used both in the training and testing phase. The performance of the system was evaluated using the free response receiver operating characteristic (FROC) curve, where the true positive fraction was plotted as a function of the average number of false positives per image [17]. The FROC curve is applicable to situations such as diagnostic imaging that involve multiple detections on a single image. We considered a detection of a cluster as true positive, if 75% of the microcalciÔ¨Åcations are correctly detected. 3.1. MLP performance For the case of the MLP network, we tested two networks with Ô¨Åve input neurons, one output neuron and one hidden layer. More than one hidden layer may be beneÔ¨Åcial for some applications; however, one hidden layer is proved to be sufÔ¨Åcient if enough hidden neurons are used [18]. We evaluated the performance of MLP using two different topologies, one with Ô¨Åve and one with ten hidden nodes, respectively. In the training process, the weights between the neurons were adjusted iteratively so that the differences between the output values and the target

The features extracted from the original mammograms were classiÔ¨Åed using artiÔ¨Åcial neural network (ANN) classiÔ¨Åers. ANNs are non-parametric pattern recognition systems that can generalize by learning from examples. We evaluated the classiÔ¨Åcation capabilities of two different networks (multi layer perceptron‚ÄîMLP and radial basis function network-RBFN) with a varied number of hidden nodes (nodes in the hidden layers). RBF networks and MLP networks are both universal approximators; therefore, there always exists an RBF network capable of ‚Äò‚Äòmimicking‚Äô‚Äô the performance of a given MLP and vice versa [16]. In the present work, the number of hidden neurons was estimated experimentally. The neural networks were trained using 107

ARTICLE IN PRESS
1566 S. Halkiotis et al. / Signal Processing 87 (2007) 1559‚Äì1568

Fig. 9. FROC curve of the RBF network. Fig. 8. FROC curve of the MLP.

values were minimized. The networks were trained using a back-propagation adaptive learning rate training function, so the learning rate changed during the training process, as the algorithm moved across the performance surface. The learning step size was kept as large as possible while keeping learning stable. The MLP with ten hidden nodes achieved the best classiÔ¨Åcation rate. The system misclassiÔ¨Åed one mammogram as normal, achieving a sensitivity of 94.7% with an average of 0.27 false positive Ô¨Åndings (FPF) per image. The misclassiÔ¨Åed image was a mammogram with a single benign calciÔ¨Åcation. Using the MLP with Ô¨Åve hidden nodes, two mammograms were misclassiÔ¨Åed as normal, achieving a sensitivity of 84.2% with an average of 0.26 false positive Ô¨Åndings (FPF) per image (Fig. 8). 3.2. RBF network performance The RBF network is composed of one hidden layer and one output linear layer. We evaluated the performance of the RBF network using two different topologies, with Ô¨Åve and ten hidden nodes, respectively. The hidden nodes were radial basis function neurons and the network output was simply the linear summation of the weighted basis functions. The centers and the widths of the radial basis functions were optimized employing the k-means algorithm. The weights in the output layer are computed using the least-mean-squares algorithm [16]. The network was trained using the same training sample that was used for the MLP. Both networks achieved the same true positive rate. The system misclassiÔ¨Åed one mammogram as normal, achieving

Fig. 10. A detected cluster of microcalciÔ¨Åcations.

a sensitivity of 94.7% with an average of 0.41 FPF/ image using the RBFN with ten hidden nodes and 0.52 FPF/image using the RBFN with Ô¨Åve hidden nodes (Fig. 9). Fig. 10 demonstrates a region containing a detected cluster of microcalciÔ¨Åcations. 4. Conclusions‚Äîfurther research It is well known that mammogram interpretation is a very difÔ¨Åcult task even for experienced radiologists. Mathematical morphology proves to be a useful tool for the detection of microcalciÔ¨Åcations in digital mammograms. In this work we have proposed a new algorithm for the detection of microcalciÔ¨Åcations on mammograms. The basic idea was to evaluate the dynamics of microcalciÔ¨Åcations, since each calciÔ¨Åcation appears as an elevation if we view each mammogram as a topographic map. Every suspicious object was marked using a binary image, which was used as a mask for object extraction from the original image. The features of the extracted objects were classiÔ¨Åed using neural networks. Two different neural network architectures were employed for the classiÔ¨Åcation of the extracted

ARTICLE IN PRESS
S. Halkiotis et al. / Signal Processing 87 (2007) 1559‚Äì1568 Table 2 Performance of the neural classiÔ¨Åers MLP with MLP with RBFN with 10 nodes 5 nodes 10 nodes TPF FPF 94.70% 0.27 84.20% 0.26 94.70% 0.413 RBFNN with 5 nodes 94.70% 0.52 1567

objects: the multilayer perceptron and the radial basis function neural network. In the experimental part, they were both seen to generalize well (Table 2). The best classiÔ¨Åcation rate was achieved using the MLP with ten hidden nodes. Several techniques have been reported in the literature for the detection of microcalciÔ¨Åcation clusters using various methodologies and different data sets. The proposed method is totally based on a series of morphological transformations in order to segment microcalciÔ¨Åcation. Zhao et al. suggested a method to extract suspicious microcalciÔ¨Åcations using mathematical morphology [19]. They studied calciÔ¨Åcation structures and found that the detection of calciÔ¨Åcation can be solved by applying morphological Ô¨Åltering operations combined with a rule base provided by experienced radiologists. Denger et al. described an approach of a two-stage algorithm for spot detection and shape extraction [20]. At the Ô¨Årst stage a weighted difference of Gaussian Ô¨Ålter was applied for the noise-invariant and size-speciÔ¨Åc detection of spots. Morphological Ô¨Ålters were applied to reproduce the shape of the spots. They reported a sensitivity of 97% with speciÔ¨Åcity about 70%. The performance of the proposed method is comparable with earlier results reported by others using the same database. Norhayati et al., using a triple-ring Ô¨Ålter analysis, reported a sensitivity of 95.8% with an average false positive rate of 1.8 clusters/image [21]. Papadopoulos et al., using a hybrid neural network classiÔ¨Åer, reported a sensitivity of 94% with an average rate of 2.70 false positive clusters/image [17]. Moreover, the performance of our method depends on the imaging properties of the MIAS mammograms. As the imaging properties of the selected mammograms may affect the performance of our method, further evaluation of the performance of the proposed algorithm using different databases is prompted. One important factor concerning the imaging properties of the mammograms is the optical density range of the Ô¨Ålm scanner. Basically, a Ô¨Ålm digitizer converts optical density information present in the radiographic

image into pixel values, which are interpreted by the computer to create the digital image. Feeding our algorithm with mammograms that were digitized using different Ô¨Ålm scanners, it would be almost impossible to correctly segment the microcalciÔ¨Åcations, because the imaging properties of the microcalciÔ¨Åcations may be signiÔ¨Åcantly altered. Another aspect that may affect the performance of our method is the spatial resolution of the mammograms, since the pixel size is used for measuring the size of the extracted objects. Despite the above comments, it can be reasonably argued that the parametric structure of the proposed algorithm allows for reliable detection using mammograms from different databases. The key parameters that should be varied in order to render the algorithm able to handle different data sets with different spatial resolutions are the sizes of the structuring elements employed in the morphological processing steps of the proposed method. References
